{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b3ac93a7-a405-4856-a5ef-e7762cc3c82c","content":"Here's what you need to change:\n\n### 1. Update packages\n\nRemove **Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk** and update **NUnit3TestAdapter** to **4.6.0+** (you're already there). Then add:\n\n```xml\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.NUnit\" Version=\"1.*\" />\n```\n\n### 2. Enable the new platform\n\nAdd this to your `.csproj` (in a `<PropertyGroup>`):\n\n```xml\n<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n```\n\n### 3. (Optional) Generate an entry point\n\nIf you want your test project to be a standalone executable:\n\n```xml\n<GenerateTestingPlatformEntryPoint>true</GenerateTestingPlatformEntryPoint>\n```\n\n### 4. Run tests\n\n```bash\ndotnet test\n```\n\nstill works, but the underlying runner is now Microsoft.Testing.Platform instead of VSTest.\n\n### Key differences to be aware of\n\n- **`--filter`** syntax changes slightly — Microsoft.Testing.Platform uses `--filter` with its own query syntax.\n- **`.runsettings`** — most settings carry over, but verify any VSTest-specific nodes.\n- **TRX output** — use `--results-directory` and `--report-trx` (add `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` if you need TRX).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"65813447-91dd-44f3-b402-72ca820cc112","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating an NUnit test project from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform. This is a knowledge question about .NET testing infrastructure - I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":409,"requestId":"BD08:2F6EDC:1E76920:221F455:6A07C429"},"id":"4990eaf9-3d59-45dc-b691-edd4266dce1b","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:11:17.229Z","parentId":"ac081f33-1dc1-405f-8787-7f76080edf26"}
